ments are forced to weaken labor and environmental standards to retain current contracts or attract new business. The essays in this volume argue that, on the contrary, under certain circumstances global economic integration can actually lead to the strengthening of consumer and environmental standards. This volume extends the argument of David Vogel’s book Trading Up, which discussed environmental standards, by focusing on the impact of globalization on labor rights, women’s rights and capital market regulations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCarr, Christopher J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelmas, Magali A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelb, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGitterman, Daniel P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKagan, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKagan, Robert A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKelemen, R. Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Dale D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Neill, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPost, Diahanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheiber, Harry N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmons, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVictor, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogel, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVo